	<string name="info_format_html"><![CDATA[
<b>M4a</b> format is encoded with AAC audio codec has good quality and small size. <b>(recommended)</b>
<br/><br/><b>Wav</b> is uncompressed audio data format. It takes much more space than other formats. It\'s needed for specific cases.
<br/><b>3gp</b> is a multimedia container format developed for mobile telecommunication services. Use it if you need to save space.
]]></string>

	<string name="info_frequency"><b>Sample rate</b> is the number of samples of audio carried per second.
		\n<b>48kHz</b> is the sample rate used for DVDs.
		\n<b>44,1kHz</b> is the sampling rate of Audio CDs. <b>(recommended)</b>
		\n<b>22kHz</b> popular sample rate for low bit rate such as 64 kbps.
		\n <b>8kHz</b> sample rate has less bandwidth than modern telephone systems. Not suitable for any serious recording task.
		</string>

	<string name="info_frequency_html"><![CDATA[
<b>Sample rate</b> is the number of samples of audio carried per second.
<br/><br/><b>48kHz</b> is the sample rate used for DVDs.
<br/><b>44,1kHz</b> is the sampling rate of Audio CDs. <b>(recommended)</b>
<br/><b>22kHz</b> popular sample rate for low bit rate such as 64 kbps.
<br/><b>8kHz</b> sample rate has less bandwidth than modern telephone systems. Not suitable for any serious recording task.
]]></string>

	<string name="info_bitrate"><b>Bitrate</b> is size of data per second of sound. Directly affects recording quality and size.
		\n<b>256 kbps</b> good quality bitrate.
		\n<b>192 kbps</b> medium quality bitrate.
		\n<b>128 kbps</b> mid-range bitrate quality. Common bitrate for podcasts. <b>(recommended)</b>
		\n<b>96 kbps</b> generally used for speech or low-quality streaming.
		\n<b>48 kbps</b> generally acceptable only for speech.
		</string>

    <string name="info_bitrate_html"><![CDATA[
<b>Bitrate</b> is size of data per second of sound. Directly affects recording quality and size.
<br/><br/><b>256 kbps</b> good quality bitrate.
<br/><b>192 kbps</b> medium quality bitrate.
<br/><b>128 kbps</b> mid-range bitrate quality. Common bitrate for podcasts. <b>(recommended)</b>
<br/><b>96 kbps</b> generally used for speech or low-quality streaming.
<br/><b>48 kbps</b> generally acceptable only for speech.
]]></string>

	<string name="info_channels">
		<b>Stereo</b> two separate channels are recorded. This means that each stereo speaker has a different sound signal. <b>(recommended)</b>
		\n<b>Mono</b> one signal channel is recorded. It can be reproduced through several speakers, but all speakers are still reproducing the same copy of the signal.
		</string>

    <string name="info_channels_html"><![CDATA[
<b>Stereo (Dual-Channel):</b> Records two independent audio channels to create a sense of space and direction. <b>(Recommended)</b>
<br/><br/><b>Mono (Single-Channel):</b> Records a single audio channel. The same signal is played through all speakers.
]]></string>

    <string name="info_audio_source_html"><![CDATA[
<b>Default:</b> The manufacturer\'s recommended setting. It usually behaves like the <b>Mic</b> option but allows the device to apply its own optimized hardware tuning.
<br/><br/><b>Mic:</b> The standard microphone setting. Best for general recording. It balances voice volume automatically while capturing the natural atmosphere of surroundings.
<br/><br/><b>Voice Communication:</b> Specifically designed for clarity of the human voice. Best for Bluetooth as it activates noise and echo cancellation.
<br/><br/><b>Unprocessed:</b> Captures raw audio without any system filters or adjustments. No background noise removal and no volume leveling. Best for high-fidelity or professional use.
]]></string>
